		<band height="150">
			<staticText>
				<reportElement positionType="Float" x="25" y="0" width="545" height="150" uuid="6d83d42b-a96a-4b01-921e-bccd80b4baeb"/>
				<textElement textAlignment="Justified" verticalAlignment="Middle" markup="html">
					<font size="12" pdfFontName="net/sf/jasperreports/fonts/dejavu/DejaVuSerif-Italic.ttf" isPdfEmbedded="true"/>
				</textElement>
				<text><![CDATA[In general, the quality of genomic DNA can be influenced by inadequate blood collection procedures/storage/shipping conditions and DNA isolation procedures. Blood should be collected in appropriate venous whole blood collection tubes containing an anticoagulant such as EDTA or acid citrate dextrose (ACD),  and their catalogue and lot number should be documented. EDTA as an anticoagulant is preferable for most genomic DNA analyses. Heparin as an anticoagulant can impact the purity of the isolated genomic DNA, which is why any method must ensure that heparin is eliminated. Carry-over of heparin into genomic DNA eluate can cause inhibitions in analytical tests, such as PCR.]]></text>
			</staticText>
		</band>
